00:51:20,793 --> 00:51:26,305
you can always count on one afternoon
when you least expect it.

499
00:51:26,505 --> 00:51:31,332
The fog slides in a milky barrier

500
00:51:31,868 --> 00:51:37,534
hangs just below the street lamps.
It cuts everything off!

501
00:51:38,499 --> 00:51:42,777
Iike a white blade. And it's magic!

502
00:51:44,761 --> 00:51:49,605
Houses lose their top floors,
trees lose their branches,

503
00:51:49,970 --> 00:51:56,067
St. Louis Cathedral loses its spires,
people passing by they lose their heads.

504
00:51:56,167 --> 00:52:00,109
So from the neck up everything disappears.

505
00:52:00,985 --> 00:52:04,369
All you can see in Jackson Square
is a bunch of decapitated bodies,

506
00:52:04,375 --> 00:52:07,834
stumbling around
and bumping into each other saying:

507
00:52:08,008 --> 00:52:10,051
"How's your mama and them?"

508
00:52:11,664 --> 00:52:15,256
That's it!
Too bad it doesn't last long.

509
00:52:15,756 --> 00:52:17,827
But how do you know all these things ?

510
00:52:23,273 --> 00:52:25,066
You know,

511
00:52:25,233 --> 00:52:31,698
ever since I came on board,
I been hearing a lot of talk about a guy.

512
00:52:31,927 --> 00:52:36,264
He got this name runs on like
a Georgia freight train.

513
00:52:36,883 --> 00:52:43,032
He's supposed to have been born on this ship and never been off it since.

514
00:52:43,332 --> 00:52:45,084
Crazy story.

515
00:52:45,384 --> 00:52:48,470
Twenty years without ever setting foot on land?

516
00:52:48,470 --> 00:52:49,625
Twenty-seven.

517
00:52:49,625 --> 00:52:54,155
They say this guy makes music
that's never been heard before.

518
00:52:54,155 --> 00:52:55,707
I've heard of him, too.

519
00:52:55,807 --> 00:53:00,406
First off, I thought you were the guy.

520
00:53:00,430 --> 00:53:03,460
- But then something didn't add up.
- Of course.

521
00:53:03,460 --> 00:53:04,713
I figured:

522
00:53:04,713 --> 00:53:10,195
if he's Nineteen Hundred
how could he know New Orleans so well?

523
00:53:10,295 --> 00:53:14,235
Because you've been to New Orleans.

524
00:53:14,240 --> 00:53:18,113
If I told you I'd never set foot in that town,
would you believe me?

525
00:53:24,260 --> 00:53:28,097
Whoever you are,
Max Tooney.

526
00:53:29,367 --> 00:53:30,535
Glad to meet you.

527
00:53:46,051 --> 00:53:47,731
How we doing?

528
00:53:47,831 --> 00:53:50,412
We're supposed to blow it up

529
00:53:50,512 --> 00:53:54,061
not wait for it to be eaten by the fishes!

530
00:53:54,100 --> 00:53:59,485
We're almost done,
just laying the last charges.

531
00:54:03,911 --> 00:54:06,479
Where the hell are you going ?

532
00:54:06,504 --> 00:54:07,948
- I have to look for someone.
- Stop him!

533
00:54:07,948 --> 00:54:10,796
It's not eazy....

534
00:54:10,797 --> 00:54:12,841
Get down there....

535
00:54:15,246 --> 00:54:18,493
You bastards, let me on board !

536
00:54:22,292 --> 00:54:24,911
Could you run that by me again?
I don't think I got the straight.

537
00:54:25,011 --> 00:54:26,864
You bet. I'll run that by you again.

538
00:54:26,964 --> 00:54:32,228
You're not going to blow up a goddamn thing,
'cause my best friend's on this ship.

539
00:54:32,841 --> 00:54:34,947
You'll all be responsible for murder.

540
00:54:34,972 --> 00:54:36,155
Get him out of here.

541
00:54:36,156 --> 00:54:38,807
Do whatever you want,
but get him off my case!

542
00:54:38,832 --> 00:54:41,469
I'm not making this up and I'm not crazy.

543
00:54:41,469 --> 00:54:43,873
If I tell you there's a man aboard the Virginian,
it means there is !

544
00:54:43,873 --> 00:54:47,389
Jesus Christ,
it means there's a man aboard the Virginian.

545
00:54:47,400 --> 00:54:51,672
We cleaned that scuttle from stem to stern.
Not even doorknobs were left.

546
00:54:51,672 --> 00:54:54,018
Only dynamite. Dynamite!
Lots of dynamite.

547
00:54:54,019 --> 00:54:55,909
How can you be so sure
that's a man on board?

548
00:54:55,910 --> 00:54:57,638
If you've any proof, out with it.

549
00:54:57,640 --> 00:55:00,330
Because I'm the horse's arse
who has to throw that switch.

550
00:55:00,340 --> 00:55:01,926
I'm sure he's there.

551
00:55:03,292 --> 00:55:06,814
I spent the best years of my life
on the Virginian.

552
00:55:10,814 --> 00:55:14,327
Did you find an upright piano
in third class ?

553
00:55:16,819 --> 00:55:21,490
The Virginian is the only ship in the world
with a piano in third class.

554
00:55:21,690 --> 00:55:25,584
Was there or wasn't there
an upright piano in third class ?

555
00:55:25,684 --> 00:55:29,805
Well, there was a piano in third class,
but it was not right. It was horizontal.

556
00:55:29,820 --> 00:55:31,420
Even it was round,

557
00:55:31,425 --> 00:55:34,790
I don't see what the hell is the goddamned piano
got to do with a ghost aboard that ship?

558
00:55:34,890 --> 00:55:38,154
there's thousands of poor dead souls
hanging out of that hospital ship!

559
00:55:38,254 --> 00:55:41,387
Get out of my sight,
or I'll call the police.

560
00:55:41,487 --> 00:55:43,538
You kick off your hands off me !

561
00:55:44,160 --> 00:55:45,380
Listen...

562
00:55:45,380 --> 00:55:51,011
Amongst those thousands of dead souls
is the greatest piano player in the world !

563
00:55:51,015 --> 00:55:53,590
Yet don't say:
a bleeding piano player.

564
00:55:53,591 --> 00:55:56,308
And what were you doing
all those years aboard the Virginian?

565
00:55:56,310 --> 00:55:57,788
Tuning the strings?

566
00:55:58,152 --> 00:56:00,407
What was I doing on the Virginian ?

567
00:56:02,920 --> 00:56:04,449
What were you doing ?

568
00:56:11,574 --> 00:56:13,384
I played!

569
00:56:14,549 --> 00:56:16,153
Ladies and gentlemen,

570
00:56:16,190 --> 00:56:17,948
Meine Damen und Herren,

571
00:56:18,048 --> 00:56:20,133
Signore e signori,

572
00:56:20,135 --> 00:56:21,535
Mesdames et Messieurs,

573
00:56:21,540 --> 00:56:24,991
Bill Douglas here to
welcomes you aboard the Virginian.

574
00:56:25,091 --> 00:56:30,763
And wishes you a pleasant evening
in the accompany of the Atlantic Jazz Band !

575
00:56:34,854 --> 00:56:36,689
Perfetto !

576
00:56:39,959 --> 00:56:43,717
Please, Nineteen Hundred,
just the normal notes. Okay?

577
00:56:56,545 --> 00:56:59,465
We played because
the ocean is big and scary.

578
00:56:59,565 --> 00:57:02,502
We played so that people
wouldn't feel the time passing

579
00:57:02,503 --> 00:57:05,311
and could forget where
and who they were.

580
00:57:05,314 --> 00:57:07,657
We played to make them dance,

581
00:57:07,757 --> 00:57:12,577
because when you dance you can't die and you feel like god.

582
00:57:12,677 --> 00:57:14,440
We played ragtime,

583
00:57:14,441 --> 00:57:18,182
because that's the music God dances to,
when nobody's watching him,

584
00:57:18,183 --> 00:57:20,298
assuming that God is black !

585
00:57:25,574 --> 00:57:26,636
End of the line boys !

586
00:57:27,202 --> 00:57:33,588
Jesus, I must be a real sinner.
Is that it, God ?

587
00:57:49,602 --> 00:57:51,738
Right! Look he'd done !

588
00:57:52,557 --> 00:57:54,321
It's sweet!

589
00:58:21,637 --> 00:58:23,614
But it was in third class

590
00:58:23,639 --> 00:58:27,504
that Nineteen Hundred
played the music which was really his.

591
00:58:27,604 --> 00:58:30,755
He'd go in the afternoons
or late at night,

592
00:58:30,756 --> 00:58:33,689
when he didn't have to play the normal notes.

593
00:58:33,690 --> 00:58:38,195
And his music was made of notes
that were everything but normal.

594
01:00:04,075 --> 01:00:06,659
What the hell do you think about
when you're playing?

595
01:00:06,759 --> 01:00:10,284
Where does your mind go?
when you hit the keys?

596
01:00:11,285 --> 01:00:14,135
Last night
I was in a beautiful country.

597
01:00:15,470 --> 01:00:19,070
Women had perfume in their hair.
Everything glowed.

598
01:00:19,227 --> 01:00:21,229
And it was full of tigers.

599
01:00:21,683 --> 01:00:23,331
He traveled.

600
01:00:23,350 --> 01:00:26,163
And each time he ended up someplace different.

601
01:00:26,164 --> 01:00:30,135
In the heart of London,
on a train in the middle of the country,

602
01:00:30,136 --> 01:00:32,371
on the edge of a giant volcano,

603
01:00:32,471 --> 01:00:35,534
in the biggest church in the world,

604
01:00:35,535 --> 01:00:39,975
counting the columns
and staring up at the crucifixes.

605
01:00:40,957 --> 01:00:42,650
He travelled.

606
01:00:43,286 --> 01:00:46,751
Guaglio', facci sentire una bella tarantella!
(Hey, man, play us a tarantella !)

607
01:00:46,812 --> 01:00:49,996
E tu fammi capire come fa questa tarantella, paisa'!
(Tell me how the tarantella goes, man !)

608
01:01:11,614 --> 01:01:15,933
The people getting off the ship
would talk about a strange music

609
01:01:15,934 --> 01:01:21,663
and a pianist who looked like
he had four hands, for all the notes he was hit.

610
01:01:30,260 --> 01:01:33,686
Weird tales circulated,
some even true.

611
01:01:33,890 --> 01:01:36,877
Like the one about an American senator
named Wilson,

612
01:01:37,077 --> 01:01:39,837
who used to travel in third class

613
01:01:39,937 --> 01:01:46,366
just to hear the music of Danny Boodman
T.D. Lemon Nineteen Hundred.

614
01:01:57,608 --> 01:01:59,581
America !

615
01:02:20,056 --> 01:02:22,767
Why did you stop ?
Please, continue.

616
01:02:24,318 --> 01:02:29,535
I'm sorry, Senator, it made port.
I only play on the open sea.

617
01:02:29,635 --> 01:02:30,980
But that's absurd.

618
01:02:30,981 --> 01:02:33,340
Ports are land to me.
I don't play on land.

619
01:02:33,440 --> 01:02:35,595
You mean, you've never gone on tour?

620
01:02:36,038 --> 01:02:37,279
What does that mean ?

621
01:02:40,490 --> 01:02:45,188
Long trips on which artists display
their talents around the world.

622
01:02:45,288 --> 01:02:49,344
In a sense, that's all I ever done.
In my way.

623
01:02:50,314 --> 01:02:51,641
Excuse me.

624
01:02:54,609 --> 01:02:56,249
Would you grant me an interview?

625
01:03:00,137 --> 01:03:02,546
An inter. . .what ?

626
01:03:03,395 --> 01:03:04,510
An interview?

627
01:03:05,686 --> 01:03:06,842
What's that ?

628
01:03:08,099 --> 01:03:09,814
The senator asks :

629
01:03:09,816 --> 01:03:15,169
Is there anything you enjoy about
when you go back to your home town?"

630
01:03:15,175 --> 01:03:16,833
Nineteen Hundred answered:

631
01:03:16,835 --> 01:03:19,815
What I like to do best in Paris is....

632
01:03:19,815 --> 01:03:25,283
wait under the Eiffeltower at sunset, for the people who throw themselves off the top

633
01:03:25,283 --> 01:03:29,607
and try to guess what country
they're from by their screams

634
01:03:29,607 --> 01:03:32,959
before they go splat
all over the ground !

635
01:03:41,645 --> 01:03:46,258
Why the hell don't you get off?
Just once? One time?

636
01:03:47,488 --> 01:03:52,047
See the world for yourself
with your own eyes?

637
01:03:54,411 --> 01:03:57,937
You ever think about it?
You could do anything you wanted to.

638
01:03:58,291 --> 01:04:01,367
People would go crazy for you.

639
01:04:02,593 --> 01:04:05,587
You could make beaucoup bucks, man.

640
01:04:05,687 --> 01:04:10,396
Get yourself the finest house,
Get yourself a wife.

641
01:04:11,684 --> 01:04:13,045
Why not ?

642
01:04:20,280 --> 01:04:25,580
God knows you can't spend the rest of your life
traveling back and forth like some yo-yo.

643
01:04:25,680 --> 01:04:30,858
The world is out there.
Nothing but a gangplank to cross.

644
01:04:30,990 --> 01:04:35,537
And what's a gangplank?
A few stupid steps.

645
01:04:35,538 --> 01:04:39,483
Christ, everything is waiting
at the bottom of those steps.

646
01:04:40,012 --> 01:04:42,180
Why don't you just do it?

647
01:04:42,987 --> 01:04:44,474
One time.

648
01:04:45,321 --> 01:04:48,052
Why don't you just get off?

649
01:04:54,302 --> 01:04:57,824
Why? Why? Why?

650
01:04:58,130 --> 01:04:59,964
Why? Why?

651
01:05:04,048 --> 01:05:05,990
I think you land people

652
01:05:07,061 --> 01:05:10,200
waste a lot of time wondering why.

653
01:05:12,559 --> 01:05:14,734
Winter comes and
you can't wait for summer.

654
01:05:14,734 --> 01:05:17,844
Summer comes and
you live in dread of winter.

655
01:05:18,454 --> 01:05:21,189
That's way you never tire of traveling.

656
01:05:21,290 --> 01:05:26,744
Always chasing someplace far away
where it's always summer.

657
01:05:30,579 --> 01:05:32,467
Doesn't sound like a good bet to me.

658
01:05:45,373 --> 01:05:48,616
Hold it, stop everything !

659
01:05:48,716 --> 01:05:50,681
Tell them to lose the detonators.

660
01:05:50,683 --> 01:05:52,297
Unhook them !

661
01:05:52,322 --> 01:05:54,213
What's going on, boss?

662
01:06:33,985 --> 01:06:37,071
If I were you, I'll pray hard we'll find somebody hidden on this paterost.

663
01:06:37,072 --> 01:06:41,036
Even somebody who can mistake a three-legged cockroach for a piano.

664
01:06:41,408 --> 01:06:44,004
It's like looking for a needle in a haystack.

665
01:06:46,642 --> 01:06:49,315
Sir, i found it.

666
01:06:50,755 --> 01:06:52,770
This was his cabin.

667
01:09:18,393 --> 01:09:21,277
Forgive me for allowing myself to,

668
01:09:21,280 --> 01:09:23,909
your music was so strong.

669
01:09:29,453 --> 01:09:32,505
Northern ltaly, I'll bet.

670
01:09:32,507 --> 01:09:36,154
Bravo, Friuli, to be exact.

671
01:09:36,157 --> 01:09:38,856
But don't stop playing. suona.

672
01:09:46,783 --> 01:09:48,827
Want a cicca?

673
01:09:52,728 --> 01:09:55,370
You don't look too happy
to be going to America.

674
01:09:55,958 --> 01:09:56,959
It's not America.

675
01:10:04,084 --> 01:10:07,078
It's everything I leave behind.

676
01:10:07,337 --> 01:10:11,495
Until a few years ago
I know only my field.

677
01:10:11,497 --> 01:10:16,299
The world for me started and ended there
in that little piece of the land.

678
01:10:16,378 --> 01:10:19,773
I never walked down
the main street of a city.

679
01:10:21,390 --> 01:10:23,786
Maybe you can't understand, but....

680
01:10:24,852 --> 01:10:26,889
I understand that perfectly.

681
01:10:29,394 --> 01:10:32,621
I know someone
who went through something very similar.

682
01:10:32,654 --> 01:10:35,949
And one fine day
did his field go dry, too?

683
01:10:36,389 --> 01:10:39,407
And did his wife also run off with a priest?

684
01:10:42,093 --> 01:10:47,100
And did the fever take his five children?

685
01:10:47,891 --> 01:10:50,256
No. But he ended up alone, too.

686
01:10:52,382 --> 01:10:54,713
Then he is more lucky than me

687
01:10:55,570 --> 01:10:58,957
I still have a daughter.
The young one.

688
01:10:59,057 --> 01:11:00,779
She survived.

689
01:11:01,193 --> 01:11:07,064
And it's for her that I decide
one day to fight against my bad luck,

690
01:11:07,164 --> 01:11:09,625
and travel all over without a destination.

691
01:11:11,795 --> 01:11:18,885
And then one day, when I go through
one of the many towns I never see before,

692
01:11:19,285 --> 01:11:24,623
I come to a hill,
And then I see...

693
01:11:24,624 --> 01:11:27,069
the most beautiful thing in my life.

694
01:11:28,502 --> 01:11:29,762
The sea !

695
01:11:30,167 --> 01:11:31,408
The sea?

696
01:11:32,236 --> 01:11:34,219
I never see it before.

697
01:11:35,369 --> 01:11:38,844
It was like lightning hit me.

698
01:11:38,845 --> 01:11:41,665
Because I hear the voice.

699
01:11:42,837 --> 01:11:44,283
The voice of the sea?

700
01:11:44,284 --> 01:11:46,369
Yeah, the voice of the sea.

701
01:11:49,163 --> 01:11:51,148
I've never heard it.

702
01:11:52,106 --> 01:11:55,667
The voice of the sea,
it is like a shout.

703
01:11:55,700 --> 01:11:58,233
A shout big and strong,

704
01:11:58,234 --> 01:12:02,352
screaming and screaming.
And the thing it was screaming was:

705
01:12:02,881 --> 01:12:04,763
"You !

706
01:12:07,322 --> 01:12:09,746
with shit instead brains!

707
01:12:10,819 --> 01:12:14,887
life is immense,
can you understand that?

708
01:12:16,475 --> 01:12:18,448
lmmense !"

709
01:12:18,903 --> 01:12:23,305
I never think of it that way.
A revolution was in my head.

710
01:12:24,270 --> 01:12:28,933
That's how I suddenly
decide to change my life,

711
01:12:30,427 --> 01:12:32,782
to start fresh.

712
01:12:34,725 --> 01:12:38,556
Change life. Start fresh.

713
01:12:38,656 --> 01:12:40,882
Tell that to your friend.

714
01:12:42,060 --> 01:12:44,104
1900!

715
01:12:45,814 --> 01:12:49,851
1900!

716
01:12:50,777 --> 01:12:54,309
It's Max Tooney, your friend.

717
01:12:54,311 --> 01:12:58,907
Come on out, Nineteen Hundred!
I'm your friend, too.

718
01:12:58,910 --> 01:13:03,645
Even if we've never met.
Don't worry, no cops !

719
01:13:20,954 --> 01:13:24,261
You said something about a piano.
Where was it exactly?

720
01:13:24,262 --> 01:13:26,231
We found it over there.

721
01:13:30,749 --> 01:13:34,076
Nineteen Hundred !

722
01:13:35,754 --> 01:13:39,070
Nineteen Hundred !

723
01:13:52,026 --> 01:13:54,121
Ladies and gentlemen,

724
01:13:54,715 --> 01:13:56,789
Meine Damen und Herren,

725
01:13:56,889 --> 01:13:59,244
Signore e signori,

726
01:13:59,344 --> 01:14:01,747
Mesdames et Messieurs,

727
01:14:01,847 --> 01:14:08,850
maestro Bill Douglas here,
welcoming you on board the Virginian.

728
01:14:09,707 --> 01:14:17,166
wishing you a very pleasant evening
in the accompany of the Atlantic Jazz Band !

729
01:14:17,167 --> 01:14:21,444
On the violin yours truly, Bill Douglas!
(The role's name should be Fritz Hermann)

730
01:14:22,300 --> 01:14:25,739
Tuba and bass, Freddie Loyacano!

731
01:14:27,013 --> 01:14:29,369
Max Tooney on trumpet!

732
01:14:31,143 --> 01:14:35,100
Jim Jim Breath Gallup
on trombone !

733
01:14:36,184 --> 01:14:39,253
Sam Scalisi on the drums !

734
01:14:41,047 --> 01:14:45,840
On saxophone,
Sam Sleepy Washington !

735
01:14:46,366 --> 01:14:49,744
On banjo,
Oscar Delaguerra !

736
01:14:49,745 --> 01:14:52,914
And finally, on piano,

737
01:14:53,187 --> 01:14:57,030
Danny Boodman T.D. Lemon Nineteen Hundred

738
01:14:57,080 --> 01:14:59,124
The greatest !

739
01:15:15,622 --> 01:15:18,415
For the last time Nineteen Hundred, just...

740
01:15:18,415 --> 01:15:19,739
just the normal notes

741
01:15:19,839 --> 01:15:21,971
What are you doing here ?
Take your places !

742
01:15:55,678 --> 01:15:58,332
Hey, end of the line !

743
01:16:06,021 --> 01:16:10,150
You've really got over me,
you son of a dirty stoker !

