Look! Pops,
I don't have a whole lot of time here.

995
01:48:41,051 --> 01:48:43,543
Well, I do! Seeing as I have a gun.

996
01:48:44,196 --> 01:48:48,976
And now that I think of it, since when
were records made on board steamships?

997
01:48:50,035 --> 01:48:51,797
Impostor !

998
01:48:52,359 --> 01:48:54,300
If that music really was played by your friend,

999
01:48:54,301 --> 01:48:57,296
it means that at some time in his life he got off that ship!

1000
01:48:57,496 --> 01:48:58,705
Correct?

1001
01:48:58,730 --> 01:49:00,297
Not a chance, Pops.

1002
01:49:00,445 --> 01:49:03,479
He cut this passionate recording personally.

1003
01:49:03,480 --> 01:49:05,514
I think it's his best work!

1004
01:49:05,520 --> 01:49:09,924
But he didn't jump ship to do it,
not even for a second.

1005
01:49:09,930 --> 01:49:15,252
It was an extraordinary, unique event
in the history of record-making.

1006
01:49:15,253 --> 01:49:18,304
The sky's the limit Mr. Nineteen Hundred.

1007
01:49:18,305 --> 01:49:22,108
If this record sells like hotcakes and we think it will,

1008
01:49:22,110 --> 01:49:24,515
you'll go far, Mr. Nineteen.

1009
01:49:24,719 --> 01:49:27,471
Do you mind if I call you Nineteen?

1010
01:49:27,571 --> 01:49:29,172
This is going to hurt, isn't it?

1011
01:49:29,215 --> 01:49:32,394
Ready now, gentelmen.
On the count.

1012
01:49:32,494 --> 01:49:35,883
And one, two, three.

1013
01:52:32,248 --> 01:52:35,189
Oh, Nineteen!

1014
01:52:35,214 --> 01:52:40,585
That is one amazing piece of music.
What is it called?

1015
01:52:41,487 --> 01:52:45,069
It's going to have people crying buckets.

1016
01:52:45,169 --> 01:52:48,618
It's got to have the right title though,
something catchy like....

1017
01:52:48,620 --> 01:52:51,097
"Swinging in the Breeze" or...

1018
01:52:51,462 --> 01:52:53,853
Great, as usual.

1019
01:52:53,853 --> 01:52:55,451
..."Sweet Nineteen," that's it...

1020
01:52:55,551 --> 01:52:57,836
You're going to be big time.

1021
01:52:57,840 --> 01:53:00,663
And all you got to do is take that big step.

1022
01:53:05,073 --> 01:53:06,526
What big step?

1023
01:53:06,530 --> 01:53:08,069
Getting off.

1024
01:53:08,169 --> 01:53:12,384
Getting off these lousy planks of wood and going after...

1025
01:53:13,009 --> 01:53:16,603
going after your fame and fortune.

1026
01:53:16,692 --> 01:53:20,263
I don't mean to butt in fellas, but...

1027
01:53:20,270 --> 01:53:27,907
with this, you can have anything you want
and never have to set foot off this boat.

1028
01:53:44,479 --> 01:53:48,275
We'll print millions of copies,

1029
01:53:48,350 --> 01:53:53,930
so that people all over the world
can hear your wonderful music, Nineteen.

1030
01:53:55,523 --> 01:53:57,358
Mr Nineteen ?

1031
01:53:57,466 --> 01:54:00,474
I won't let my music
go anywhere without me.

1032
01:54:03,306 --> 01:54:04,992
No! Don't touch.

1033
01:54:04,992 --> 01:54:06,737
What are you doing? You can't do that.

1034
01:54:06,837 --> 01:54:09,593
We have a contract.
You can't go back now.

1035
01:54:10,371 --> 01:54:12,046
I always go back.

1036
01:55:15,728 --> 01:55:17,521
Miss,

1037
01:55:20,216 --> 01:55:24,720
I'd be pleased if you...

1038
01:55:36,215 --> 01:55:40,428
Miss, I'd be...

1039
01:55:42,297 --> 01:55:44,507
I'd be thrilled...

1040
01:55:46,050 --> 01:55:49,512
if you'd accept this...

1041
01:55:51,597 --> 01:55:54,851
small token...

1042
01:57:11,594 --> 01:57:15,681
Hey, Miss Padoan, what are you doing
here all alone? Counting the waves?

1043
01:57:15,757 --> 01:57:18,879
The captain said we'd be passing
the Tropic of Cancer soon.

1044
01:57:18,880 --> 01:57:21,434
Great! At least we'll have
something to look at.

1045
01:57:21,604 --> 01:57:25,173
You ever notice how the sea changes colors? Ten times a day.

1046
01:57:25,200 --> 01:57:29,374
Even more.
I could look at the sea all day long.

1047
01:57:29,375 --> 01:57:31,351
You know farmers don't ever look at the sea.

1048
01:57:31,351 --> 01:57:34,067
It scares them At least that's what I heard.

1049
01:57:34,167 --> 01:57:35,919
That's not true.

1050
01:57:36,769 --> 01:57:41,065
Once, my father told me he heard the ocean's voice.

1051
01:57:41,374 --> 01:57:43,842
Really? What did it say?

1052
01:57:44,953 --> 01:57:48,122
I can't tell you. It's a secret.

1053
01:57:48,529 --> 01:57:50,461
And secrets should be kept.

1054
01:57:50,490 --> 01:57:53,811
Gosh, it's really coming down now.
Let's get back inside.

1055
01:57:53,812 --> 01:57:55,068
Come on !

1056
01:57:55,682 --> 01:57:57,174
Let me take your arm.

1057
01:58:56,716 --> 01:58:59,064
"Women's dormitory 3 class"

1058
02:03:01,177 --> 02:03:03,179
America

1059
02:03:03,411 --> 02:03:07,561
Damn it,
I wanted to say it !

1060
02:03:36,724 --> 02:03:38,904
Excuse me.

1061
02:03:39,977 --> 02:03:41,390
Excuse me.

1062
02:03:43,124 --> 02:03:44,627
Sorry.

1063
02:03:46,492 --> 02:03:48,045
Please, miss.

1064
02:03:51,404 --> 02:03:53,062
I have to talk to you.

1065
02:03:59,679 --> 02:04:02,029
You're meeting your father, aren't you?

1066
02:04:02,303 --> 02:04:03,773
Yes.

1067
02:04:04,556 --> 02:04:05,740
How did you know?

1068
02:04:05,765 --> 02:04:07,668
I think I've met him.

1069
02:04:11,583 --> 02:04:15,753
On this ship,
quite a few years ago.

1070
02:04:16,102 --> 02:04:18,516
I don't know if he took this same ship.

1071
02:04:19,075 --> 02:04:22,365
I'm sure of it.

1072
02:04:23,960 --> 02:04:27,018
He has a musette. Yes?

1073
02:04:28,739 --> 02:04:30,741
I think we played together.

1074
02:04:32,002 --> 02:04:36,632
I don't know if he'd remember,
 but...say hello to him.

1075
02:04:38,016 --> 02:04:41,086
All right, I will.

1076
02:04:41,152 --> 02:04:45,531
But how did you know who I was?
It's very strange, no?

1077
02:04:45,640 --> 02:04:47,642
It's a secret.

1078
02:04:49,034 --> 02:04:51,911
And secrets should be kept.

1079
02:04:51,988 --> 02:04:54,590
Although I think your father
felt differently back then.

1080
02:04:56,073 --> 02:05:00,153
Come on! Keep moving! Or we'll be here all week to discipline!

1081
02:05:19,582 --> 02:05:23,412
Please accept this...
small musical token.

1082
02:05:23,469 --> 02:05:26,345
I'm sorry, but I can't hear you.

1083
02:05:27,340 --> 02:05:33,753
I want you to...
accept this small token.

1084
02:05:34,511 --> 02:05:36,301
I can't hear you.

1085
02:05:41,555 --> 02:05:42,894
Good luck.

1086
02:05:42,994 --> 02:05:45,670
Thank you. Good luck to you, too.

1087
02:05:47,121 --> 02:05:49,790
Why don't you come and visit us some day?

1088
02:05:49,795 --> 02:05:52,984
We live on Mott Street. Number 27.

1089
02:05:52,985 --> 02:05:55,145
My father has a fish shop.

1090
02:05:56,173 --> 02:05:57,810
Maybe....

1091
02:06:05,202 --> 02:06:08,626
Padoan, okay. Next.

1092
02:06:08,690 --> 02:06:10,221
Next.

1093
02:06:52,466 --> 02:06:56,410
He never mentioned her to me again,
and I never asked.

1094
02:06:56,450 --> 02:06:59,465
At least not for
the next twelve crossings.

1095
02:07:00,558 --> 02:07:03,603
Besides, he was happy
just like always.

1096
02:07:03,811 --> 02:07:06,022
His popularity was at its peak.

1097
02:07:06,780 --> 02:07:12,953
None of us could have imagined what was smoldering beneath the ashes of his apparent happiness.

1098
02:07:13,863 --> 02:07:18,676
Then, one evening in spring,
halfway between Genoa and New York,

1099
02:07:18,684 --> 02:07:20,895
right in the middle of the ocean,

1100
02:07:20,903 --> 02:07:22,776
the painting fell.

1101
02:07:22,801 --> 02:07:25,622
What do you meaning ? The painting fell?

1102
02:07:25,733 --> 02:07:29,340
Pops, have you ever asked yourself
why paintings fall ?

1103
02:07:29,350 --> 02:07:30,215
No, not really.

1104
02:07:30,216 --> 02:07:33,318
I've always been impressed
by this thing about paintings.

1105
02:07:33,319 --> 02:07:34,978
What's the painting got to do with this ?

1106
02:07:34,979 --> 02:07:36,079
It does.

1107
02:07:36,080 --> 02:07:40,240
Because for Nineteen Hundred, that night
went the way it does for paintings.

1108
02:07:40,813 --> 02:07:46,093
They hang there for years, and then
without any happening...

1109
02:07:46,093 --> 02:07:47,569
Nothing at all...

1110
02:07:49,551 --> 02:07:51,024
Down that come.

1111
02:07:51,543 --> 02:07:54,648
They're hanging there on that nail,
no-body even touches them,

1112
02:07:54,649 --> 02:07:56,624
but at a certain point...

1113
02:07:58,283 --> 02:08:04,242
They fall down anyway,
in the most absolute silence.

1114
02:08:04,445 --> 02:08:09,265
With everything perfectly still
around them.

1115
02:08:10,264 --> 02:08:14,063
Not even a fly moving.

1116
02:08:14,448 --> 02:08:16,668
And they. . .

1117
02:08:19,814 --> 02:08:24,568
There's no reason.
Why in that instant ?

1118
02:08:25,103 --> 02:08:26,739
Who knows ?

1119
02:08:31,065 --> 02:08:34,706
What happens to a nail

1120
02:08:34,707 --> 02:08:41,506
to make it decide
that it just can't anymore ?

1121
02:08:43,059 --> 02:08:46,464
Does he have a soul, too,
poor thing ?

1122
02:08:46,698 --> 02:08:48,775
Does he make decisions ?

1123
02:08:48,875 --> 02:08:50,590
Sit down....

1124
02:08:51,352 --> 02:08:54,395
Did the nail discuss this at length
with the painting ?

1125
02:08:54,397 --> 02:08:56,119
They were unsure about doing it.

1126
02:08:56,120 --> 02:08:58,531
They talked it over every night for years ?

1127
02:08:58,532 --> 02:09:04,496
And then they decide on a date,
a time, a minute, a precise instant ?

1128
02:09:05,521 --> 02:09:10,868
Or they both know it from the beginning?
Both of them was already set up ?

1129
02:09:11,133 --> 02:09:14,480
"Look! I'm letting go in seven years."

1130
02:09:14,483 --> 02:09:15,750
"Fine with me."

1131
02:09:15,850 --> 02:09:18,206
"So understand, on May 13."

1132
02:09:18,207 --> 02:09:19,127
"Okay."

1133
02:09:19,127 --> 02:09:20,165
"At twelve o'clock?"

1134
02:09:20,166 --> 02:09:21,846
"How about twelve fifteen."

1135
02:09:21,847 --> 02:09:22,986
"OK."

1136
02:09:22,987 --> 02:09:24,750
"So good night."

1137
02:09:25,634 --> 02:09:28,649
Seven years later,
on May 13,

1138
02:09:28,650 --> 02:09:31,097
at twelve fifteen....

1139
02:09:35,203 --> 02:09:37,098
It's impossible to understand.

1140
02:09:37,099 --> 02:09:39,689
It's one of those things
that probably better not to think about !

1141
02:09:39,690 --> 02:09:41,210
Because it makes you nuts.

1142
02:09:41,519 --> 02:09:42,943
Paintings fall,

1143
02:09:43,564 --> 02:09:46,846
when you wake up one morning
and discover she doesn't love you anymore,

1144
02:09:47,157 --> 02:09:50,708
when you open a newspaper
and read that war has broken out,

1145
02:09:50,962 --> 02:09:54,008
when you see a train and
you think: I got to leave this place,

1146
02:09:54,131 --> 02:09:56,494
when you look in a mirror
and realise you're old.

1147
02:09:56,975 --> 02:09:59,637
When one evening, in the middle of the ocean,

1148
02:09:59,737 --> 02:10:07,443
Nineteen Hundred looks up from his plate,
looks me in the eyes and...

1149
02:10:07,697 --> 02:10:10,146
In three days when we get to New York,
I'm getting off this ship.

1150
02:10:13,618 --> 02:10:17,521
I was flabbergasted.

1151
02:10:19,591 --> 02:10:21,593
Cat got your tongue?

1152
02:10:23,378 --> 02:10:27,133
No,I'm glad.

1153
02:10:27,782 --> 02:10:29,867
But all of a sudden?

1154
02:10:31,280 --> 02:10:32,572
All of a sudden.

1155
02:10:34,806 --> 02:10:37,073
My man...

1156
02:10:37,408 --> 02:10:38,675
That's aces.

1157
02:10:38,676 --> 02:10:40,680
I've got to see something down there.

1158
02:10:40,887 --> 02:10:42,015
What ?

1159
02:10:42,016 --> 02:10:43,520
The ocean.

1160
02:10:46,259 --> 02:10:47,543
The ocean ?

1161
02:10:47,600 --> 02:10:48,967
The ocean.

1162
02:10:54,334 --> 02:10:55,935
You're pulling my leg ?

1163
02:10:56,456 --> 02:10:59,553
You've seen nothing but the ocean
since the day you were born.

1164
02:10:59,554 --> 02:11:00,764
But from here.

1165
02:11:02,669 --> 02:11:05,533
I want to see it from there.
It's not the same thing at all.

1166
02:11:05,928 --> 02:11:08,838
Wait till we dock, lean over the side,
take a good look.

1167
02:11:08,839 --> 02:11:10,371
It's the same thing.

1168
02:11:10,925 --> 02:11:12,130
No, it's not.

1169
02:11:13,260 --> 02:11:15,413
From land, you can hear its voice.

1170
02:11:15,513 --> 02:11:17,697
You don't hear that from a ship.

1171
02:11:18,664 --> 02:11:21,244
What do you mean, its voice?

1172
02:11:21,300 --> 02:11:22,900
Its voice.

1173
02:11:26,869 --> 02:11:32,617
It's like... a big scream...

1174
02:11:34,341 --> 02:11:38,117
telling you that life is immense.

1175
02:11:38,642 --> 02:11:40,074
Once you've finally heard it,

1176
02:11:40,075 --> 02:11:43,472
then you really know
what you have to do to go on living.

1177
02:11:44,322 --> 02:11:46,762
I could stay here forever,

1178
02:11:47,980 --> 02:11:52,540
but the ocean would never tell me a thing.

1179
02:11:53,268 --> 02:11:57,461
But if I get off, live on land for a couple of years,

1180
02:11:57,462 --> 02:12:01,813
then I'll be normal. Just like the others.

1181
02:12:02,381 --> 02:12:06,047
Then maybe one day,
I'll make it to the coast,

1182
02:12:06,120 --> 02:12:10,643
look up, see the ocean,
and hear it scream.

1183
02:12:13,653 --> 02:12:18,469
I don't know who's been telling you all this
bullshit or if you're just making it up.

1184
02:12:18,714 --> 02:12:20,915
But you want to know what I think?

1185
02:12:21,817 --> 02:12:23,454
I think...

1186
02:12:24,003 --> 02:12:28,975
the real reason you want off this ship is the girl.

1187
02:12:29,486 --> 02:12:31,654
It's always the girl.

1188
02:12:31,754 --> 02:12:35,999
But even if it's not the reason,
that suits me just fine.

1189
02:12:36,616 --> 02:12:41,811
Because I've always wanted you to leave this ship and play for the people on land.

1190
02:12:41,911 --> 02:12:45,382
And marry a nice woman and have children,

1191
02:12:45,482 --> 02:12:50,711
and all those things in life which are not immense

1192
02:12:51,598 --> 02:12:53,912
but are worth the effort.

1193
02:12:55,803 --> 02:12:59,570
You'll come visit me, won't you, Max? On land?

1194
02:13:03,462 --> 02:13:05,499
Of course.

1195
02:13:07,400 --> 02:13:11,148
That way, you'll introduce me
to the mother of your children,

1196
02:13:12,439 --> 02:13:15,133
and invite me for Sunday dinner.

1197
02:13:15,581 --> 02:13:18,447
I'll bring the dessert and a bottle of wine

1198
02:13:18,448 --> 02:13:21,475
and you'll tell me I shouldn't have.

1199
02:13:21,949 --> 02:13:27,687
And while you're showing me around
your house shaped like a ship,

1200
02:13:28,337 --> 02:13:33,976
your wife will be cooking a turkey.
And then we'll sit at the table.

1201
02:13:34,043 --> 02:13:37,864
And I'll tell her she's an excellent cook,

1202
02:13:37,964 --> 02:13:41,665
and she'll say how you
talk about me all the time.

1203
02:13:45,593 --> 02:13:49,865
You know,
I'm going to give you my camel coat.

1204
02:13:50,441 --> 02:13:53,695
You'll cut a fine figure
when you get down there.

1205
02:13:57,680 --> 02:14:00,289
You think I could have a family with a horse ?

1206
02:14:11,923 --> 02:14:13,168
- Nineteen Hundred !
- Hey !

1207
02:14:13,169 --> 02:14:18,300
How many people I have seen saying goodbye
on the docks without giving a damn.

1208
02:14:19,063 --> 02:14:23,899
But when I said goodbye to
Nineteen Hundred, it was a real blow.

1209
02:14:56,486 --> 02:14:58,697
Look after yourself, all right ?

1210
02:15:09,572 --> 02:15:12,036
Take care.

1211
02:15:18,139 --> 02:15:21,184
We laughed,
we kept saying "see you soon",

1212
02:15:21,610 --> 02:15:25,959
But inside, we both knew
we'd never see each other again.

1213
02:15:26,214 --> 02:15:30,729
And there was nothing we could do
about it, it had to happen that way.

1214
02:15:30,901 --> 02:15:33,321
And now it was happening.

1215
02:15:54,199 --> 02:15:55,849
How the hell we get off?

1216
02:16:01,829 --> 02:16:04,524
Goodbye, Nineteen Hundred, take care.

1217
02:16:04,524 --> 02:16:06,871
- Bye !
- Don't forget us.

1218
02:16:06,872 --> 02:16:09,642
Remember to wear your
woollen vest in winter.

1219
02:16:09,643 --> 02:16:11,808
Take care Nineteen Hundred, take care.

1220
02:16:11,809 --> 02:16:13,742
Write us a letter sometimes.

1221
02:16:14,340 --> 02:16:16,922
- Take care yourself!
- Give my regards to Broadway.

1222
02:16:19,165 --> 02:16:20,547
Good luck !

1223
02:16:54,750 --> 02:16:56,801
What'd he do, step in shit?

1224
02:16:57,968 --> 02:16:59,728
Maybe he just forgot something.

1225
02:16:59,780 --> 02:17:01,937
Maybe he's forgotten
why he's getting off.

1226
02:18:14,440 --> 02:18:16,442
What's he doing ?

1227
02:18:40,475 --> 02:18:44,145
Whatever he saw
from that damned gangplank,

1228
02:18:44,553 --> 02:18:48,877
what kind of thoughts
crossed his mind standing up there,

1229
02:18:48,983 --> 02:18:50,985
he never told me.

1230
02:18:52,792 --> 02:18:56,254
- No, go away !
- Wait !

1231
02:18:56,565 --> 02:19:00,152
I'll give you all the money I have,
take it.

1232
02:19:02,289 --> 02:19:07,974
He was strange for a long time after that.
He wouldn't talk to anyone.

1233
02:19:08,369 --> 02:19:12,999
He preferred keeping to
himself for days and days.

1234
02:19:13,207 --> 02:19:16,848
He seemed taken by very personal matters.

1235
02:19:17,020 --> 02:19:20,570
Then, one day,
while I was sitting at the bar...

1236
02:19:20,775 --> 02:19:21,975
Look!

1237
02:19:30,805 --> 02:19:33,418
Thanks for the coat, Max.
Fit like a glove.

1238
02:19:34,737 --> 02:19:36,964
It was a real shame.

1239
02:19:38,441 --> 02:19:42,449
I'm much better now.
I'm done with all that.

1240
02:19:52,656 --> 02:19:55,454
He looked like somebody
who wasn't kidding,

1241
02:19:55,554 --> 02:19:58,605
one who knew
exactly where he was going.

1242
02:19:59,281 --> 02:20:02,511
Like when he'd sit at the piano
and start to play.

1243
02:20:03,293 --> 02:20:05,965
There were no doubts in his hands.

1244
02:20:06,065 --> 02:20:10,449
It was as the keys had been
waiting for those notes forever.

1245
02:20:10,748 --> 02:20:13,859
It seemed like he'd made them up
then and there,

1246
02:20:13,959 --> 02:20:20,109
yet somewhere in his head, those
notes had been written all along.

1247
02:20:20,808 --> 02:20:22,772
Now, I know that on that day,

1248
02:20:22,775 --> 02:20:27,365
Nineteen Hundred had decided to sit before the keyboard of his life

1249
02:20:27,420 --> 02:20:30,591
and start playing his most absurd music.

1250
02:20:31,077 --> 02:20:35,670
And this music would have marked the rest of his days.

1251
02:21:31,629 --> 02:21:36,042
Look at that guy with the trumpet,
he's got be drunk or half crazy.

1252
02:21:36,049 --> 02:21:39,042
Look! He's crying as he plays!

1253
02:22:03,547 --> 02:22:08,462
I left the Virginian on
August 21st, 1933,

1254
02:22:08,562 --> 02:22:13,517
with my leave papers and back pay.
Everything in order.

1255
02:22:13,517 --> 02:22:16,632
I knew that sooner or later
I'd have been through with the ocean.

1256
02:22:16,633 --> 02:22:18,827
So that's what I did.

1257
02:22:19,485 --> 02:22:23,383
I heard no more about
Nineteen Hundred or the Virginian.

1258
02:22:23,673 --> 02:22:26,013
Not that I ever forgot them.

1259
02:22:26,113 --> 02:22:27,739
On the contrary.

1260
02:22:28,287 --> 02:22:30,642
During the war, I'd always ask myself...

1261
02:22:31,262 --> 02:22:35,128
Who knows what Nineteen Hundred
would do if he were here?

1262
02:22:35,150 --> 02:22:37,316
Who knows what he'd say?

1263
02:22:37,500 --> 02:22:39,794
Fuck war, he'd say.

1264
02:22:39,989 --> 02:22:44,694
But said by me,
it wasn't the same thing.

1265
02:23:05,874 --> 02:23:07,554
A lot of time's gone by, you know.

1266
02:23:08,622 --> 02:23:10,168
Who could say he really didn't leave?

1267
02:23:10,169 --> 02:23:13,777
Maybe one fine day, he went to Mott Street, the fish shop, to ask for the woman.

1268
02:23:15,117 --> 02:23:17,009
Maybe.

1269
02:27:25,658 --> 02:27:30,162
Hey, Conn, what's the matter?
You lose your sea legs?

1270
02:27:33,208 --> 02:27:36,317
Where the hell did you find that record ?

1271
02:27:44,182 --> 02:27:47,051
What have you been up to all these years ?

1272
02:27:53,284 --> 02:27:55,201
Making music.

1273
02:27:55,689 --> 02:27:57,670
Even during the war?

1274
02:28:00,902 --> 02:28:05,019
Even when no one was dancing anymore.

1275
02:28:08,409 --> 02:28:11,028
Even when the bombs were falling.

1276
02:28:14,457 --> 02:28:17,802
The music helped them get better.

1277
02:28:19,196 --> 02:28:21,092
The wounded, I mean.

1278
02:28:25,405 --> 02:28:30,141
Or else it kept them entertained,

1279
02:28:30,673 --> 02:28:34,654
as they slipped away into another world.

1280
02:28:36,846 --> 02:28:41,267
Sometimes they didn't even mind the voyage

1281
02:28:41,776 --> 02:28:44,612
if they could listen to the music.

1282
02:28:47,148 --> 02:28:50,478
Mine was the last face they saw.

1283
02:28:52,178 --> 02:28:57,518
And I kept playing
till the ship got here.

1284
02:29:02,180 --> 02:29:04,599
Call this a ship ?

1285
02:29:05,302 --> 02:29:09,358
It's more like a mountain of dynamite about to explode.

1286
02:29:10,088 --> 02:29:12,748
A bit dangerous, don't you think ?

1287
02:29:18,840 --> 02:29:20,633
And you, Max ?

1288
02:29:22,775 --> 02:29:24,360
Where's your trumpet?

1289
02:29:26,896 --> 02:29:29,960
I gave it up as well, a while back.

1290
02:29:30,383 --> 02:29:34,512
But, you know, now I'm in the
mood for starting again.

1291
02:29:35,445 --> 02:29:38,490
I'm busting with new ideas.

1292
02:29:39,634 --> 02:29:42,678
Let's start a duo,
you and me.

1293
02:29:43,638 --> 02:29:46,107
Or our own band :

1294
02:29:46,374 --> 02:29:52,338
The "Danny Boodman T.D. Lemon
Nineteen Hundred Big Band !"

1295
02:29:53,056 --> 02:29:57,006
It gets the blood going !
We'd be a smash.

1296
02:30:00,263 --> 02:30:03,577
Come on, Nineteen Hundred.
Come with me. Let's get off.

1297
02:30:04,133 --> 02:30:06,126
We'll watch the fireworks from the pier,

1298
02:30:06,128 --> 02:30:09,172
and then we'll start from scratch.

1299
02:30:10,786 --> 02:30:13,585
Sometimes that's the way you have to do it.

1300
02:30:13,586 --> 02:30:16,637
You go right back to the beginning.

1301
02:30:28,061 --> 02:30:33,782
"You're never really done for
as long as you've got a good story

1302
02:30:33,783 --> 02:30:36,486
and someone to tell it to".

1303
02:30:37,148 --> 02:30:38,923
Remember?

1304
02:30:40,720 --> 02:30:43,039
You told me that.

1305
02:30:45,659 --> 02:30:49,615
Well, what a stack of stories you got now!

1306
02:30:50,505 --> 02:30:53,373
The world would be hanging
on your every word,

1307
02:30:54,617 --> 02:30:58,168
and they'd go crazy for your music.

1308
02:31:00,740 --> 02:31:02,123
Believe me.

1309
02:31:07,847 --> 02:31:10,308
All that city. . .

1310
02:31:15,539 --> 02:31:19,036
You just couldn't see an end to it.

1311
02:31:20,743 --> 02:31:22,639
The end !

1312
02:31:23,496 --> 02:31:28,547
please?
You please just show me where it ends?

1313
02:31:31,930 --> 02:31:35,048
It was all very fine
on that gangway

1314
02:31:35,470 --> 02:31:39,568
and I was grand, too,
in my overcoat.

1315
02:31:40,246 --> 02:31:42,825
I cut quite a figure.

1316
02:31:43,516 --> 02:31:48,706
And I was getting off, Guaranteed.

1317
02:31:49,631 --> 02:31:52,467
That's wasn't the problem.

1318
02:31:56,179 --> 02:31:59,865
It wasn't what I saw that stopped me, Max.

1319
02:32:00,975 --> 02:32:03,560
It was what I didn't see.

1320
02:32:04,353 --> 02:32:06,374
Can you understand that ?

1321
02:32:08,032 --> 02:32:10,651
What I didn't see.

1322
02:32:11,653 --> 02:32:16,293
In all that srawling city,
there was everything except an end.

1323
02:32:18,043 --> 02:32:20,321
There was no end.

1324
02:32:22,345 --> 02:32:28,312
What I did not see was
where the whole thing came to an end,

1325
02:32:30,321 --> 02:32:32,790
the end of the world.

1326
02:32:39,922 --> 02:32:42,122
You take a piano.

1327
02:32:43,726 --> 02:32:47,893
Keys begin, the keys end.

1328
02:32:49,290 --> 02:32:53,474
You know there are 88 of them,
nobody can tell you any different.

1329
02:32:53,828 --> 02:32:58,138
They are not infinite,
you are infinite.

1330
02:32:59,784 --> 02:33:05,013
And on those keys, the music that you can make is infinite.

1331
02:33:05,723 --> 02:33:08,026
I like that.

1332
02:33:08,434 --> 02:33:10,645
That I can live by.

1333
02:33:10,954 --> 02:33:12,584
You get me up on that gangway

1334
02:33:12,584 --> 02:33:13,895
and you roll out in front of me

1335
02:33:13,895 --> 02:33:17,909
a keyboard of millions and billions of keys that never end.

1336
02:33:17,909 --> 02:33:21,481
And that's the truth, Max,
that they never end.

1337
02:33:21,798 --> 02:33:24,375
That keyboard is infinite.

1338
02:33:25,276 --> 02:33:30,406
And if that keyboard is infinite,
then on that keyboard there is no music you can play.

1339
02:33:31,232 --> 02:33:33,885
You're sitting on the wrong bench.

1340
02:33:34,686 --> 02:33:37,264
That's God's piano.

1341
02:33:40,300 --> 02:33:45,376
Christ, did you see the streets? Just the streets.
There were thousands of them.

1342
02:33:46,030 --> 02:33:49,723
How do you do it down there?
How do you choose just one?

1343
02:33:50,968 --> 02:33:55,568
One woman, one house,

1344
02:33:56,457 --> 02:34:00,825
one piece of land to call your own,
one landscape to look at,

1345
02:34:01,938 --> 02:34:04,547
one way to die.

1346
02:34:07,927 --> 02:34:10,639
All that world just weighing down on you.

1347
02:34:10,639 --> 02:34:12,669
You don't even know where it comes to an end.

1348
02:34:12,769 --> 02:34:16,709
I mean, aren't you ever just scared of breaking apart at the thought of it?

1349
02:34:16,709 --> 02:34:19,813
At the enormity of living it?

1350
02:34:23,835 --> 02:34:26,361
I was born on this ship.

1351
02:34:29,807 --> 02:34:37,228
And the world passed me by,
but two thousand people at a time.

1352
02:34:38,891 --> 02:34:41,728
And there were wishes here,

1353
02:34:43,146 --> 02:34:46,816
but never more than fit between prow and stern.

1354
02:34:48,994 --> 02:34:53,884
You played out your happiness
on a piano that was not infinite.

1355
02:34:54,699 --> 02:34:57,785
I learned to live that way.

1356
02:35:01,314 --> 02:35:03,107
Land?

1357
02:35:05,293 --> 02:35:08,817
Land is a ship too big for me.

1358
02:35:10,999 --> 02:35:14,074
It's a woman too beautiful.

1359
02:35:15,945 --> 02:35:20,785
It's a voyage too long.
Perfume too strong.

1360
02:35:21,960 --> 02:35:25,533
It's music I don't know how to make.

1361
02:35:29,058 --> 02:35:32,126
I could never get off this ship.

1362
02:35:35,073 --> 02:35:39,699
At best, I can step off my life.

1363
02:35:41,971 --> 02:35:46,484
After all, I don't exist for anyone.

1364
02:35:50,705 --> 02:35:53,541
You're the exception, Max.

1365
02:35:55,276 --> 02:35:58,520
You're the only one
who knows that I'm here.

1366
02:36:00,615 --> 02:36:03,076
You're a minority.

1367
02:36:03,784 --> 02:36:06,689
And you'd better get used to it.

1368
02:36:11,017 --> 02:36:13,324
Forgive me, my friend.

1369
02:36:14,979 --> 02:36:17,559
But I'm not getting off.

1370
02:37:47,622 --> 02:37:49,207
Hey, Max.

1371
02:37:51,567 --> 02:37:54,116
Picture the scene at the Golden Gates.

1372
02:37:54,528 --> 02:37:58,424
Some guy searching a list trying to find my name, not finding it.

1373
02:37:59,426 --> 02:38:01,656
What did you say your name was again?

1374
02:38:01,756 --> 02:38:03,424
Nineteen Hundred.

1375
02:38:04,622 --> 02:38:09,862
Niemann, Nightingale, Ninestock...
Nittledeen?

1376
02:38:09,962 --> 02:38:12,793
Well, you see, sir. I was born on a ship.

1377
02:38:13,615 --> 02:38:14,719
Beg your pardon?

1378
02:38:14,722 --> 02:38:19,129
Born, raised, and died on a ship.
Maybe I'm not registered there.

1379
02:38:19,229 --> 02:38:22,730
Yeah, Shipwreck ?

1380
02:38:22,830 --> 02:38:25,779
No, six and a half tons of dynamite.

1381
02:38:28,399 --> 02:38:30,161
Feeling better now?

1382
02:38:30,261 --> 02:38:34,629
Yeah, I'm fine, except I lost an arm.

1383
02:38:34,929 --> 02:38:36,467
An arm ?

1384
02:38:36,567 --> 02:38:38,978
Yes, in the explosion.

1385
02:38:40,842 --> 02:38:43,073
Well, you should be able to find one over there.

1386
02:38:44,287 --> 02:38:46,602
Which one did you say you were missing?

1387
02:38:46,702 --> 02:38:48,447
Left, sir.

1388
02:38:48,958 --> 02:38:52,844
I'm dreadfully sorry.

1389
02:38:53,729 --> 02:38:57,515
We only seem to have two rights.

1390
02:38:57,615 --> 02:38:58,882
Two right arms?

1391
02:38:58,883 --> 02:39:00,707
Yes.

1392
02:39:00,807 --> 02:39:02,616
Afraid so.

1393
02:39:02,717 --> 02:39:07,007
Would you mind awfully if....

1394
02:39:08,187 --> 02:39:09,623
If I what?

1395
02:39:09,723 --> 02:39:13,789
Well, if you take a right arm instead of a left?

1396
02:39:17,286 --> 02:39:22,828
Well, all things considered, a right arm than nothing, I suppose.

1397
02:39:22,928 --> 02:39:25,246
Couldn't agree more.

1398
02:39:25,598 --> 02:39:30,862
By the way, we have one black arm
and one white arm.

1399
02:39:30,900 --> 02:39:33,828
Oh, no.... matching color, please.

1400
02:39:33,828 --> 02:39:39,608
I have nothing against the other race,
but it's just a question of aesthetics.

1401
02:39:43,085 --> 02:39:45,504
No laughing matter, Max.

1402
02:39:47,033 --> 02:39:52,892
What a cock-up, Spend eternity with two right arms?

1403
02:39:53,306 --> 02:39:56,424
I mean, how would you make the sign of the cross?

1404
02:40:11,382 --> 02:40:13,336
Hey, Max.

1405
02:40:14,995 --> 02:40:18,215
Imagine the music I could play with two right arms.

1406
02:40:19,440 --> 02:40:22,284
Hope I can find a piano up there.

1407
02:40:29,609 --> 02:40:32,175
Okay, that's fine like that.

1408
02:40:40,041 --> 02:40:44,614
- Slowly.
- Get hold of it there.

1409
02:42:18,301 --> 02:42:20,796
What would you have done in my shoes?

1410
02:42:22,888 --> 02:42:24,890
I don't know.

1411
02:42:27,585 --> 02:42:30,839
I wouldn't probably have felt quite useless.

1412
02:42:38,338 --> 02:42:43,862
Sooner or later all stories end,
and there's nothing left to add.

1413
02:42:49,148 --> 02:42:52,084
Anyhow, thanks, pops.

1414
02:43:13,147 --> 02:43:18,602
Conn, there's just one thing I don't get.

1415
02:43:19,670 --> 02:43:23,421
Who hid the broken record inside the piano?

1416
02:43:26,564 --> 02:43:28,305
You're looking at him.

1417
02:43:29,934 --> 02:43:33,938
So you weren't so useless after all.

1418
02:43:42,652 --> 02:43:44,237
Conn.

1419
02:43:48,249 --> 02:43:49,876
Here.

1420
02:43:53,413 --> 02:43:58,167
Take your trumpet.
Well, you'll be needing it.

1421
02:44:00,425 --> 02:44:01,535
But I....

1422
02:44:01,687 --> 02:44:03,439
Never mind the money.

1423
02:44:04,107 --> 02:44:07,505
A good story's worth more than an old trumpet.

1424
02:44:15,159 --> 02:44:17,161
Okay, Pops.

1425
02:45:13,282 --> 02:45:25,122
La Leggenda Del Pianista Sull'oceano

1426
02:45:26,534 --> 02:45:29,703
Giuseppe Tornatore